{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a040a65d3b96a558", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tESCUCHA: A Spanish Speech Benchmark for Heterogeneous Acoustic Conditions\n2\tTitle:\n3\tContent selection saved. Describe the issue below:\n4\tDescription:\n5\tarXiv is now an independent nonprofit!\n6\tLearn more\n7\t×\n8\tLicense: CC BY 4.0\n9\tarXiv:2607.17812v1 [cs.CL] 20 Jul 2026\n10\tESCUCHA: A Spanish Speech Benchmark for Heterogeneous Acoustic Conditions\n11\t1\n12\tst\n13\tFernando López\n14\t†\n15\t2\n16\tnd\n17\tAna Ayala\n18\t†\n19\t3\n20\trd\n21\tGuillermo Segovia\n22\t4\n23\tth\n24\tFernando Ibáñez\n25\t5\n26\tth\n27\tAna Martínez\n28\t6\n29\tth\n30\tPablo Gómez\n31\t7\n32\tth\n33\tJordi Luque\n34\tAbstract\n35\tAs large audio language models (LALMs) advance, robust evaluation frameworks have become essential. In this context, Spanish speech understanding under realistic acoustic conditions has received particularly little attention. We introduce ESCUCHA, the first Spanish speech understanding benchmark designed to evaluate LALMs across heterogeneous acoustic conditions and reasoning abilities. ESCUCHA comprises 1,000 human-curated questions paired with audio, totaling 162.9 hours sourced directly “from the wild” rather than drawn from existing datasets, with durations ranging from a few seconds to over 80 minutes. The benchmark emphasizes reasoning, spanning 9 perceptual and 10 reasoning categories, and it captures linguistic diversity through multiple Spanish accents and non-normative speech. ESCUCHA further includes multi-audio questions, spoken questions, and audio instructions, and it flags which questions support open-ended evaluation. Benchmarking several state-of-the-art multimodal and speech models reveals substantial performance gaps relative to trained humans.\n36\tI\n37\tIntroduction\n38\tUnderstanding auditory information is essential to machine intelligence. Numerous large audio language models (LALMs) have emerged in response, including LTU\n39\t[\n40\t1\n41\t]\n42\t, SALMONN\n43\t[\n44\t2\n45\t]\n46\t, GAMA\n47\t[\n48\t3\n49\t]\n50\t, Qwen3-Omni\n51\t[\n52\t4\n53\t]\n54\t, Kimi-Audio\n55\t[\n56\t5\n57\t]\n58\t, and Audio Flamingo 3\n59\t[\n60\t6\n61\t]\n62\t.\n63\tEvaluating these models is critical for ranking their performance and exposing their limitations, and thereby advancing the field. Early benchmarks targeted foundational tasks such as speech recognition and speech translation\n64\t[\n65\t7\n66\t,\n67\t8\n68\t,\n69\t9\n70\t,\n71\t10\n72\t]\n73\t. More recent efforts evaluate perception and reasoning jointly, including MMAU\n74\t[\n75\t11\n76\t]\n77\t, MMAR\n78\t[\n79\t12\n80\t]\n81\t, SAKURA\n82\t[\n83\t13\n84\t]\n85\t, MMSU\n86\t[\n87\t14\n88\t]\n89\t, and MMAU-Pro\n90\t[\n91\t15\n92\t]\n93\t.\n94\tDespite this growth, it remains unclear whether strong performance on existing benchmarks transfers once models move beyond English and beyond normative speech. High scores under normative, English-centric conditions do not guarantee that a model will generalize to other languages and speaker characteristics, and current benchmarks offer little guidance on the expected degradation. This concern is acute for non-normative speech: neuromotor disorders such as amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) and post-stroke conditions frequently cause dysarthria, which impairs neuromuscular control of speech, reduces articulation clarity, alters prosody, and yields variable intelligibility, all of which challenge speech recognition systems\n95\t[\n96\t16\n97\t,\n98\t17\n99\t]\n100\t.\n101\tThe gap is particularly concerning for practitioners who aim to deploy LALMs in non-English contexts. Multilingual benchmarks offer only limited relief: GlobeAudio spans six languages but excludes Spanish\n102\t[\n103\t18\n104\t]\n105\t, while Fleurs-SLU\n106\t[\n107\t19\n108\t]\n109\tevaluates speech-LLMs on Spanish only as one language among many, and through a narrow set of reading-comprehension questions derived from text, whose answers are recoverable from a transcript. For Spanish specifically, initial efforts such as IberoBench\n110\t[\n111\t20\n112\t]\n113\ttarget the Iberian languages, but IberoBench is a multi-task text benchmark for the natural language understanding of large language models (LLMs) rather than a speech benchmark. For non-normative speech, meanwhile, prior work centers on transcription, leaving speech understanding uncovered\n114\t[\n115\t21\n116\t]\n117\t. More broadly, existing benchmarks concentrate on English and normative speech, rely on read or curated audio rather than audio in the wild, restrict themselves to a limited range of question types, and, being derived from existing datasets, risk train-test contamination.\n118\tTo close this gap, we introduce\n119\tESCUCHA\n120\t, the first speech understanding benchmark for evaluating LALMs in Spanish, spanning both normative and non-normative speech sourced under real-world conditions.\n121\tESCUCHA\n122\tfollows the multiple-choice question answering (MCQA) protocol and additionally includes multi-audio comparative questions, audio instruction following (AIF), and spoken questions, which together characterize how LALMs perform on Spanish across diverse conditions. Our main contributions are as follows:\n123\t•\n124\tThe first\n125\tin-the-wild\n126\tSpanish benchmark (audio and questions) for evaluating large audio language models.\n127\t1\n128\t1\n129\t1\n130\tDownload code and annotations:\n131\thttps://github.com/ferugit/ESCUCHA\n132\t•\n133\tThe first LALM benchmark to evaluate speech understanding and reasoning over non-normative pathological speech, spanning amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) and stroke.\n134\t•\n135\tA broad evaluation of current LALM behavior on Spanish, covering open-weight and closed models, text-only baselines, and human performance.\n136\tII\n137\tThe ESCUCHA Benchmark\n138\tII-A\n139\tOverview\n140\tESCUCHA\n141\tcomprises 1,000 expert-curated questions grounded in 162.9 hours of in-the-wild Spanish audio sourced from publicly available recordings. Following the MMAU-Pro design philosophy\n142\t[\n143\t15\n144\t]\n145\t, we annotate every question along two complementary axes: the\n146\tperceptual\n147\tskills required to extract information from the signal, and the\n148\treasoning\n149\tskills required to transform that information into an answer, yielding a multi-label taxonomy of 9 perception and 10 reasoning categories. Questions carry 1.44 perception labels and 1.14 reasoning labels on average, reflecting the compositional nature of realistic audio understanding: a single item frequently demands, for example, both paralinguistic emotion recognition and causal reasoning about speaker intent. An example appears in Figure\n150\t1\n151\t: the item combines non-normative speech from an ALS patient with temporal and quantitative reasoning, requiring the model to recognize two numerical values, place them on a shared timeline, and compare them.\n152\tExample Question\n153\tAudio context:\n154\tA 96-second testimony in which Irene, a 28-year-old woman with non-normative speech who was diagnosed with ALS (\n155\tELA\n156\t), recounts the date of her diagnosis and cites the life expectancy typically given to patients with the disease.\n157\tQuestion:\n158\t¿Desde que le diagnosticaron la ELA, ha vivido Irene más tiempo del que se\n159\tmenciona en el vídeo como esperanza de vida para las personas con esta\n160\tenfermedad?\n161\tSince Irene was diagnosed with ALS, has she lived\n162\tlonger than the life expectancy mentioned in the video for people with this disease?\n163\t(A)\n164\tHa vivido menos.\n165\tShe has lived less.\n166\t(B)\n167\tHa vivido más.\n168\t✓\n169\t\\checkmark\n170\tShe has lived longer.\n171\t(C)\n172\tNo puede saberse.\n173\tIt cannot be determined.\n174\t(D)\n175\tHa vivido lo mismo.\n176\tShe has lived the same amount of time.\n177\tPerception:\n178\tLexical & Phrase-Level Recognition\n179\tReasoning:\n180\tQuantitative Reasoning (Counting/Arithmetic Comparison)\n181\t⋅\n182\t\\cdot\n183\tTemporal & Ordering Reasoning\n184\tFigure 1:\n185\tExample of chained cross-category reasoning.\n186\tThe question requires three steps: recognizing two numerical values (time since Irene’s diagnosis and the life expectancy she cites), mapping them onto a shared timeline, and comparing them. The most frequent failure is selecting (C)\n187\t“No puede saberse,”\n188\twhich conflates the absence of an explicit comparison in the audio with genuine unknowability.\n189\tESCUCHA also features a\n190\tcomparative\n191\tsubset: 254 questions (25.4%) reference two separate recordings and require the model to relate them, comparing speakers, dialects, acoustic conditions, or content across clips. Such cross-clip comparison is common in professional listening tasks. Table\n192\tI\n193\tsummarizes the main statistics of the benchmark.\n194\tTABLE I:\n195\tESCUCHA at a glance. AIF: audio instruction following;\n196\tMCQA: multiple-choice question answering. Comparative, spoken, and non-normative are non-exclusive tags and do not partition the total.\n197\tStatistic\n198\tValue\n199\tTotal questions\n200\t1,000\n201\tMCQA\n202\t900\n203\tAIF\n204\t100\n205\tNon-exclusive questions\n206\tComparative (two-audio)\n207\t254\n208\tSpoken questions\n209\t100\n210\tNon-normative speech\n211\t158\n212\tPerception / reasoning categories\n213\t9 / 10\n214\tMean labels per question (perc. / reas.)\n215\t1.44 / 1.14\n216\tDuration per question (median / mean)\n217\t1.4 min / 9.8 min\n218\tDuration range\n219\t0.1 min – 85.2 min\n220\tTotal audio (sum over questions)\n221\t162.9 h\n222\tII-B\n223\tBenchmark Creation Process\n224\tWe construct ESCUCHA through the four-stage pipeline illustrated in Figure\n225\t2\n226\t.\n227\tFigure 2:\n228\tPipeline for constructing the ESCUCHA benchmark. The process comprises four stages: (i) target setting and refinement of the perception and reasoning categories; (ii) audio selection and authoring of questions and distractors; (iii) LLM-assisted review; and (iv) model and human evaluation.\n229\t•\n230\tTargets and category refinement.\n231\tWe define the target of each question type, the categories, and the type of audio to collect, then revise the perception and reasoning taxonomy. Section\n232\tII-C\n233\tprovides further detail.\n234\t•\n235\tAudio selection and question authoring.\n236\tWe source audio from in-the-wild YouTube recordings, favoring spontaneous speech. Annotators identify candidate videos, filter the content, author the corresponding questions and distractors, ground each item in the audio, and assign its perception and reasoning labels. For non-normative speech, we retrieve videos using Spanish queries targeting dysarthric speech, such as condition-specific keywords, interviews, and documentaries, with a preference for interviews; we then filter candidates on the basis of self-reported diagnoses, video metadata, and perceptual evidence of non-normative speech. The resulting corpus spans acoustically diverse conditions, including background noise, music, and heterogeneous recording setups.\n237\t•\n238\tLLM-assisted review.\n239\tWe review each question along four dimensions with an LLM (\n240\tGemma-4-31B-IT\n241\t), which returns the identifiers of the items it flags for manual verification by annotators. The review checks whether the categories are correctly assigned, whether the audio is required to answer the question, whether the distractors are sufficiently challenging, and whether the question or distractors contain grammatical errors.\n242\t•\n243\tModel and human evaluation.\n244\tWe benchmark a range of LALMs, text-only LLMs, and cascade systems, and we collect human judgments to establish reference performance.\n245\tAcross all four stages, the annotation team consists of three linguists and three technical experts, all native Spanish speakers. Each item carries metadata, including source URLs, measured durations, multi-label categories, distractors, and, where applicable, pathological speaker attributes and AIF verifier identifiers.\n246\tII-C\n247\tTaxonomy\n248\tWe derive our taxonomy from MMAU-Pro\n249\t[\n250\t15\n251\t]\n252\t, retaining its perception and reasoning axes while slightly redefining them. Table\n253\tII\n254\tpresents the category counts for our benchmark.\n255\tTABLE II:\n256\tQuestion counts per perception and reasoning category. Counts sum to more than 1,000 because the taxonomy is multi-label.\n257\tCategory\n258\t#Q\n259\tPerception\n260\tLexical and Phrase-Level Recognition\n261\t506\n262\tSpeaker Identification\n263\t324\n264\tParalinguistic/Emotion Recognition\n265\t181\n266\tSpeech Activity, Turn-Taking and Overlap Detection\n267\t115\n268\tLanguage Identification\n269\t87\n270\tAudio Quality, Artifacts & Channel Characteristics\n271\t84\n272\tProsody Detection\n273\t74\n274\tSpeaker Demographics\n275\t50\n276\tSyntactic and Sentence-Structure Processing\n277\t18\n278\tReasoning\n279\tSpeaker Intent, Pragmatics and Causal Reasoning\n280\t221\n281\tSemantic Abstraction and Summarization\n282\t177\n283\tLogical/Consistency Reasoning\n284\t159\n285\tGround Truth and World Knowledge Integration\n286\t133\n287\tQuantitative Reasoning\n288\t121\n289\tTemporal and Ordering Reasoning\n290\t105\n291\tSocial Role and Relationship Inference\n292\t94\n293\tComparative and Preference-Based Judgments\n294\t62\n295\tCross-frontier Entity Linking\n296\t38\n297\tCoherence and Discourse Structure\n298\t29\n299\tRather than enforce a uniform distribution, we prioritized questions that were challenging and well grounded in each recording over questions that would merely fill under-represented cells. This preserves difficulty while still covering every category. The co-occurrence matrix (Fig.\n300\t3\n301\t) characterizes the distribution that emerged. It is densely populated rather than block-diagonal: lexical recognition co-occurs with all ten reasoning categories, peaking with semantic abstraction and summarization (158), while other perceptual skills pair more selectively, such as language identification with ground-truth and world-knowledge integration (53). This mix of one broad row and several localized pairings shows that many questions combine perception and reasoning rather than isolating a single skill. A few specific pairings remain unpopulated, which we leave to future work.\n302\tFigure 3:\n303\tPerception\n304\t×\n305\t\\times\n306\treasoning co-occurrence across the 900 MCQA questions. AIF questions only with perception labels, were excluded. Each cell counts question label pairs; questions carrying multiple perception or reasoning labels contribute to several cells, so cell totals exceed the question count and row and column sums are not disjoint.\n307\tII-D\n308\tOther Tasks\n309\tBeyond regular covered tasks,\n310\tESCUCHA\n311\tincludes two further subsets.\n312\tNon-normative speech.\n313\tA subset of 158 questions (15.8%) targets pathological speech, with per-speaker metadata covering diagnosis, sex, and intelligibility. It includes speakers with ALS (114 questions) and post-stroke speech (44), annotated by sex (123 male, 35 female). We also provide intelligibility levels for 145 of the 158 items, ranging from Low (53) and Medium/Low (71) to Medium (9) and High/Medium (12); the remaining 13 ALS items lack an intelligibility annotation.\n314\tSpoken questions.\n315\tWe sample 100 questions from the existing\n316\tESCUCHA\n317\tpool, using inverse-frequency weighting over perception and reasoning categories to prioritise underrepresented classes. Only single-audio items were eligible, since the spoken question is stored as a second associated audio. The original question text is fed to the OmniVoice\n318\t[\n319\t22\n320\t]\n321\ttext-to-speech (TTS) system, which yields varied speakers and Spanish accents. At evaluation time, the written prompt is fixed (\n322\t“Contesta a la pregunta en el audio”\n323\t, i.e., “Answer the question in the audio”), so the model must recover the actual question entirely from the spoken audio. The choices are maintained in text.\n324\tII-E\n325\tAudio Duration\n326\tThe benchmark spans four orders of magnitude in duration, from 6.7 s to 85 min per question (median 86.2 s, mean 586.5 s; for comparative items the duration is summed over both clips). Each question is assigned to one of five length buckets, reported in Table\n327\tIII\n328\t. The Long and Extended buckets jointly account for a quarter of the benchmark, allowing\n329\tESCUCHA\n330\tto stress long-context audio understanding. Figure\n331\t4\n332\tshows the full duration distribution.\n333\tTABLE III:\n334\tDistribution of questions across the five duration buckets.\n335\tBucket\n336\tRange\n337\t#Q\n338\t%\n339\tBrief\n340\t≤\n341\t30\n342\t{\\leq}30\n343\ts\n344\t123\n345\t12.3\n346\tShort\n347\t30 s–2 min\n348\t440\n349\t44.0\n350\tMedium\n351\t2–10 min\n352\t187\n353\t18.7\n354\tLong\n355\t10–30 min\n356\t127\n357\t12.7\n358\tExtended\n359\t>\n360\t30\n361\t{>}30\n362\tmin\n363\t123\n364\t12.3\n365\tTotal\n366\t1,000\n367\t100.0\n368\tFigure 4:\n369\tDistribution of audio duration per question (log scale). The dashed line marks the median (86.2 s).\n370\tII-F\n371\tEvaluation Formats\n372\tESCUCHA contains two evaluation formats. Most of the benchmark (900 questions, 90%) follows an MCQA protocol with 2–4 options (848 four-choice, 45 three-choice, 7 two-choice), enabling deterministic scoring. Independently of format, each question is annotated for whether the options are required: 712 (71.2%) are answerable without them, allowing open-ended evaluation, and 288 (28.8%) require them.\n373\tThe remaining 100 questions (10%) are\n374\taudio instruction-following\n375\t(AIF) items: open-ended tasks in which the instruction is delivered in the audio rather than the text prompt, and the response must satisfy that spoken constraint, checked by a deterministic verifier. To produce the spoken instructions, we also use the OmniVoice\n376\t[\n377\t22\n378\t]\n379\t. This design jointly probes audio comprehension and instruction following: the model must first recover the instruction from the signal and then obey it. We cover six constraint types:\n380\t•\n381\tKeyword usage\n382\t(24): include a specified connector or phrase, e.g.,\n383\tsin embargo\n384\t(“however”), or at least one numeral.\n385\t•\n386\tLength\n387\t(22): meet an exact, minimum, maximum, or bounded word or sentence count, e.g., exactly three sentences.\n388\t•\n389\tWord exclusion\n390\t(18): avoid a specified word, expression, or punctuation mark, e.g.,\n391\tmuy\n392\t(“very”).\n393\t•\n394\tOpenings/closings\n395\t(16): begin with a fixed prefix or end with a fixed suffix, e.g.,\n396\tEn resumen\n397\t(“In summary”).\n398\t•\n399\tFormatting\n400\t(12): adopt a structural form, e.g., a numbered list or sections delimited by\n401\t##\n402\theaders.\n403\t•\n404\tStyle\n405\t(8): e.g., write in lowercase only, pose the answer as questions, or repeat a keyword a number of times.\n406\tA constraint can occasionally be met without genuine compliance; word exclusion, for instance, may be satisfied by chance. The expected random-guessing accuracy is 25.61% on the MCQA subset and 23.05% on the full benchmark.\n407\tIII\n408\tExperimental Setup\n409\tWe evaluate\n410\tESCUCHA\n411\tacross four system families: end-to-end LALMs, a cascaded ASR-plus-LLM pipeline, text-only LLMs, and human and random baselines. Thus, we separate genuine audio understanding from what is recoverable through transcription alone and language bias. In our setup, multi-audio items are presented as their component clips concatenated with one second of silence between them, and all experiments run on an NVIDIA DGX Spark GPU.\n412\tIII-A\n413\tLALMs\n414\tWe evaluate several LALMs, covering open and proprietary systems of varying scale:\n415\tAudio-Flamingo-3\n416\t(8.3B)\n417\t[\n418\t6\n419\t]\n420\t,\n421\tQwen2.5-Omni\n422\t(7B),\n423\tQwen3-Omni-30B-A3B\n424\t[\n425\t4\n426\t]\n427\t,\n428\tVoxtral-Mini\n429\t(3B)\n430\t[\n431\t23\n432\t]\n433\t,\n434\tGemma-4-12B-IT\n435\t, and\n436\tGemini-2.5-Flash\n437\t.\n438\tIII-B\n439\tCascaded Systems\n440\tTo test whether audio understanding is required at all, or whether transcription suffices, we evaluate a cascade. This is a natural baseline given that lexical recognition is the most represented perception category. We transcribe each audio with\n441\tWhisper-Large-v3\n442\t[\n443\t24\n444\t]\n445\tand answer with\n446\tQwen3-4B-Instruct-2507\n447\t[\n448\t25\n449\t]\n450\t.\n451\tIII-C\n452\tText-Only LLMs\n453\tExtending the cascade logic, we evaluate text-only LLMs that never see the raw audio. These receive the questions and choices with no audio. We include\n454\tGemma-4-31B-IT\n455\t,\n456\tGemma-4-12B-IT\n457\t, and\n458\tQwen3-4B-Instruct-2507\n459\t[\n460\t25\n461\t]\n462\t.\n463\tIII-D\n464\tEvaluation Protocol\n465\tMCQA.\n466\tEach item presents a question with\n467\tN\n468\tN\n469\tlabeled options; the model must respond as\n470\t<letter>.<justification>\n471\t. Scoring is exact-match: correct if the output matches the gold string case-insensitively or its first parsed letter indexes the gold option.\n472\tAIF.\n473\tAudio instruction-following items are open-ended: a deterministic\n474\tverifier\n475\tfunction with a parameter dictionary is applied to the output, returning true or false. No model-based judge is used, so scoring is fully reproducible.\n476\tIV\n477\tResults\n478\tTable\n479\tIV\n480\treports accuracy across all models and subsets. The trained human annotator reaches 90.10% overall, far above the best model (74.40%), establishing a wide human–model gap on\n481\tESCUCHA\n482\t.\n483\tTABLE IV:\n484\tESCUCHA benchmark results (accuracy %). Best result per column is\n485\tbolded\n486\t. Pathological and Normative are MCQA subsets; Spoken Q contains items whose question is embedded in the audio.\n487\tModel\n488\tSize\n489\tMCQA\n490\tAIF\n491\tPathological\n492\tNormative\n493\tSpoken Q\n494\tOverall\n495\tBaselines\n496\tRandom\n497\t–\n498\t25.61\n499\t0.00\n500\t25.32\n501\t25.67\n502\t25.75\n503\t23.05\n504\tAlways 1st\n505\t–\n506\t26.22\n507\t0.00\n508\t24.05\n509\t26.68\n510\t23.00\n511\t23.60\n512\tAlways 2nd\n513\t–\n514\t24.33\n515\t0.00\n516\t27.22\n517\t23.72\n518\t23.00\n519\t21.90\n520\tAlways 3rd\n521\t–\n522\t26.22\n523\t0.00\n524\t25.95\n525\t26.28\n526\t30.00\n527\t23.60\n528\tAlways 4th\n529\t–\n530\t23.22\n531\t0.00\n532\t22.78\n533\t23.32\n534\t24.00\n535\t20.90\n536\tHuman\n537\t–\n538\t91.33\n539\t79.00\n540\t93.04\n541\t90.97\n542\t93.00\n543\t90.10\n544\tAudio Models\n545\tAudio-Flamingo-3-HF\n546\t8.3B\n547\t51.56\n548\t32.00\n549\t55.06\n550\t50.81\n551\t64.00\n552\t49.60\n553\tGemini-2.5-Flash\n554\t–\n555\t52.67\n556\t54.00\n557\t36.71\n558\t56.06\n559\t53.00\n560\t52.80\n561\tGemma-4-12B-IT\n562\t12B\n563\t48.11\n564\t60.00\n565\t36.08\n566\t50.67\n567\t49.00\n568\t49.30\n569\tQwen2.5-Omni-7B\n570\t7B\n571\t50.22\n572\t54.00\n573\t44.94\n574\t51.35\n575\t58.00\n576\t50.60\n577\tQwen3-Omni-30B-A3B\n578\t30B (A3B)\n579\t72.89\n580\t88.00\n581\t74.68\n582\t72.51\n583\t77.00\n584\t74.40\n585\tVoxtral-Mini-3B-2507\n586\t3B\n587\t50.22\n588\t40.00\n589\t51.90\n590\t49.87\n591\t55.00\n592\t49.20\n593\tCascaded\n594\twhisper-large-v3 + Qwen3-4B-Instruct-2507\n595\t4B\n596\t59.00\n597\t69.00\n598\t63.92\n599\t57.95\n600\t59.00\n601\t60.00\n602\tText-Only Models\n603\tGemma-4-31B-IT\n604\t31B\n605\t23.00\n606\t31.00\n607\t23.42\n608\t22.91\n609\t33.00\n610\t23.80\n611\tGemma-4-12B-IT (text)\n612\t12B\n613\t18.11\n614\t32.00\n615\t18.35\n616\t18.06\n617\t23.00\n618\t19.50\n619\tQwen3-4B-Instruct-2507\n620\t4B\n621\t42.11\n622\t31.00\n623\t46.20\n624\t41.24\n625\t48.00\n626\t41.00\n627\tAmong audio models,\n628\tQwen3-Omni-30B-A3B\n629\tstands out at 74.40% overall and leads every column among models, including a striking 88.00% on AIF that exceeds even the human score of 79.00% on that subset. Every other audio model falls between 49 and 53% overall, confirming that\n630\tESCUCHA\n631\tposes a genuine challenge.\n632\tA consistent pattern is the drop from normative to pathological speech.\n633\tGemini-2.5-Flash\n634\tand\n635\tGemma-4-12B-IT\n636\tlose 19 and 15 percentage points, respectively, on pathological items, whereas\n637\tAudio-Flamingo-3\n638\t,\n639\tQwen3-Omni-30B-A3B\n640\t, and\n641\tVoxtral-Mini\n642\thold or slightly improve. This asymmetry indicates that pathological speech remains a weak point.\n643\tComparison with MMAU-Pro\n644\t[\n645\t15\n646\t]\n647\tadds context:\n648\tAudio-Flamingo-3\n649\treaches 58.8% on the MMAU-Pro speech subset but 49.60% here, and\n650\tQwen2.5-Omni-7B\n651\tdrops similarly, from 57.4% to 50.60%. The two benchmarks are not directly comparable: they differ in question design, language, and the inclusion of pathological speech, but the gaps suggest\n652\tESCUCHA\n653\tis at least as discriminative and harder for models with limited Spanish coverage.\n654\tThe cascaded system (\n655\tWhisper-Large-v3\n656\t+\n657\tQwen3-4B-Instruct-2507\n658\t) achieves 60.00% overall, outperforming every single audio model except\n659\tQwen3-Omni-30B-A3B\n660\t. Its advantage is most pronounced on AIF (69.00%) and pathological items (63.92%), supporting the view that a large fraction of\n661\tESCUCHA\n662\tquestions are grounded in lexical understanding.\n663\tAll models receive the same system prompt, and none is instructed to guess under missing-modality conditions. The text-only\n664\tQwen3-4B-Instruct-2507\n665\treaches 41.00% overall, well above the random baseline (23.05%) and comparable to several audio systems, which we attribute to partial solvability from question structure and language priors. We therefore suggest treating this text-only model as a lower-bound baseline, alongside the positional controls, in future evaluations. The two text-only\n666\tGemma-4\n667\tvariants instead score near random (23.80% and 19.50%): lacking audio, they refuse a large fraction of items, 53% for\n668\tGemma-4-31B-IT\n669\tand 32% for\n670\tGemma-4-12B-IT\n671\t, with each refusal scored as incorrect and outputs such as requests to supply the audio for analysis.\n672\tV\n673\tLimitations\n674\tSeveral factors qualify our results. The human upper bound is optimistic: the evaluator is a trained linguist, so the reported 90.10% may differ from a regular person. On the AIF subset, some items can be answered correctly from the written instruction alone, without processing the audio, which partially inflates AIF scores and means the task does not exclusively measure audio instruction following. The pathological-speech subset is grounded in self-reported diagnoses targeting diverse speech understanding instead of clinical usage.\n675\tThe evaluation is also uneven across models and axes.\n676\tGemini-2.5-Flash\n677\tsupports long-form audio architecturally, but a payload limit in our evaluation pipeline forced us to exclude items above a size threshold, biasing its results toward shorter items and preventing a direct comparison with models run on the full set. More broadly,\n678\tESCUCHA\n679\tcovers speech exclusively, so results do not generalize to music, environmental sound, or audio effects, and the benchmark is constructed entirely in Spanish, meaning scores for models with limited Spanish data conflate audio understanding with language coverage. Cross-lingual comparisons against English-centric benchmarks such as MMAU-Pro should be made with care. Finally, the taxonomy is lexically unbalanced, with lexical and phrase-level recognition dominating the perception axis, so per-category scores in sparsely populated cells rest on few items.\n680\tVI\n681\tConclusions\n682\tWe introduced\n683\tESCUCHA\n684\t, the first in-the-wild Spanish speech benchmark for large audio-language models, and the first to evaluate reasoning over non-normative pathological speech. It pairs 1,000 curated questions with 162.9 hours of audio, annotated along a multi-label taxonomy of nine perception and ten reasoning categories, and combines MCQA with comparative multi-audio items, audio instruction following, and spoken questions.\n685\tOur evaluation reveals a wide human–model gap: the best system reaches 74.40% overall against 90.10% for a trained annotator, with most audio models near 50%. Two findings stand out. Several models degrade markedly on pathological speech, a persistent weak point for LALMs trained on clean, read audio. And a cascaded ASR-plus-LLM pipeline outperforms every single audio model but one, indicating that much of the benchmark is grounded in lexical understanding recoverable from a transcript, while the residual gap to\n686\tQwen3-Omni-30B-A3B\n687\tmarks where genuine acoustic reasoning still matters.\n688\tFuture work includes broadening the pathological subset with further neurological conditions, and populating the currently sparse perception-reasoning pairings.\n689\tAI-Generated Content Disclosure\n690\tWe used a generative AI to assist in paraphrasing and improving clarity and grammar in parts of the manuscript; all generated content was reviewed and validated by the authors.\n691\tReferences\n692\t[1]\n693\tY. Gong, H. Luo, A. H. Liu, L. Karlinsky, and J. Glass, “Listen, think, and understand,” in\n694\tProc. ICLR\n695\t, 2024.\n696\t[2]\n697\tG. Sun, W. Yu, C. Tang, X. Chen, T. Tan, W. Li, L. Lu, Z. Ma, Y. Wang, and C. Zhang, “video-salmonn: Speech-enhanced audio-visual large language models,” in\n698\tProc. ICML\n699\t, 2024.\n700\t[3]\n701\tS. Ghosh, S. Kumar, A. Seth, C. K. R. Evuru, U. Tyagi, S. Sakshi, O. Nieto, R. Duraiswami, and D. Manocha, “GAMA: A large audio-language model with advanced audio understanding and complex reasoning abilities,” in\n702\tProc. EMNLP\n703\t. Miami, Florida, USA: ACL, 2024, pp. 6288–6313. [Online]. Available:\n704\thttps://aclanthology.org/2024.emnlp-main.361/\n705\t[4]\n706\tJ. Xu, Z. Guo, H. Hu, Y. Chu, X. Wang, J. He, Y. Wang, X. Shi, T. He, X. Zhu, Y. Lv, Y. Wang, D. Guo, H. Wang, L. Ma, P. Zhang, X. Zhang, H. Hao, Z. Guo, B. Yang, B. Zhang, Z. Ma, X. Wei, S. Bai, K. Chen, X. Liu, P. Wang, M. Yang, D. Liu, X. Ren, B. Zheng, R. Men, F. Zhou, B. Yu, J. Yang, L. Yu, J. Zhou, and J. Lin, “Qwen3-omni technical report,” 2025. [Online]. Available:\n707\thttps://arxiv.org/abs/2509.17765\n708\t[5]\n709\tD. Ding, Z. Ju, Y. Leng, S. Liu, T. Liu, Z. Shang, K. Shen, W. Song, X. Tan, H. Tang\n710\tet al.\n711\t, “Kimi-audio technical report,”\n712\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2504.18425\n713\t, 2025.\n714\t[6]\n715\tS. Ghosh, A. Goel, J. Kim, S. Kumar, Z. Kong, S. gil Lee, C.-H. H. Yang, R. Duraiswami, D. Manocha, R. Valle, and B. Catanzaro, “Audio flamingo 3: Advancing audio intelligence with fully open large audio language models,” in\n716\tProc. Adv. Neural Inf. Process. Syst. (NeurIPS)\n717\t, 2025. [Online]. Available:\n718\thttps://openreview.net/forum?id=FjByDpDVIO\n719\t[7]\n720\tC.-y. Huang, K.-H. Lu, S.-H. Wang, C.-Y. Hsiao, C.-Y. Kuan, H. Wu, S. Arora, K.-W. Chang, J. Shi, Y. Peng\n721\tet al.\n722\t, “Dynamic-superb: Towards a dynamic, collaborative, and comprehensive instruction-tuning benchmark for speech,” in\n723\tProc. ICASSP\n724\t. IEEE, 2024, pp. 12 136–12 140.\n725\t[8]\n726\tQ. Yang, J. Xu, W. Liu, Y. Chu, Z. Jiang, X. Zhou, Y. Leng, Y. Lv, Z. Zhao, C. Zhou\n727\tet al.\n728\t, “Air-bench: Benchmarking large audio-language models via generative comprehension,” in\n729\tProc. ACL\n730\t. Bangkok, Thailand: ACL, Aug. 2024, pp. 1979–1998. [Online]. Available:\n731\thttps://aclanthology.org/2024.acl-long.109/\n732\t[9]\n733\tB. Wang, X. Zou, G. Lin, S. Sun, Z. Liu, W. Zhang, Z. Liu, A. Aw, and N. F. Chen, “Audiobench: A universal benchmark for audio large language models,” in\n734\tProc. NAACL:HLT\n735\t, Albuquerque, New Mexico, 2025, pp. 4297–4316.\n736\t[10]\n737\tC.-y. Huang, W.-C. Chen, S.-w. Yang, A. T. Liu, C.-A. Li, Y.-X. Lin, W.-C. Tseng, A. Diwan, Y.-J. Shih, J. Shi\n738\tet al.\n739\t, “Dynamic-superb phase-2: A collaboratively expanding benchmark for measuring the capabilities of spoken language models with 180 tasks,” in\n740\tProc. ICLR\n741\t, 2025.\n742\t[11]\n743\tS. Sakshi, U. Tyagi, S. Kumar, A. Seth, R. Selvakumar, O. Nieto, R. Duraiswami, S. Ghosh, and D. Manocha, “MMAU: A massive multi-task audio understanding and reasoning benchmark,” in\n744\tProc. ICLR\n745\t, 2024.\n746\t[12]\n747\tZ. Ma, Y. Ma, Y. Zhu, C. Yang, Y.-W. Chao, R. Xu, W. Chen, Y. Chen, Z. Chen, J. Cong\n748\tet al.\n749\t, “Mmar: A challenging benchmark for deep reasoning in speech, audio, music, and their mix,” in\n750\tProc. Adv. Neural Inf. Process. Syst. (NeurIPS) Datasets and Benchmarks Track\n751\t, 2025.\n752\t[13]\n753\tC.-K. Yang, N. Ho, Y.-T. Piao, and H. yi Lee, “SAKURA: On the Multi-hop Reasoning of Large Audio-Language Models Based on Speech and Audio Information,” in\n754\tInterspeech\n755\t, 2025, pp. 1788–1792.\n756\t[14]\n757\tD. Wang, J. Wu, J. Li, D. Yang, X. Chen, T. Zhang, and H. Meng, “MMSU: A Massive Multi-task Spoken Language Understanding and Reasoning Benchmark,”\n758\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2506.04779\n759\t, 2025.\n760\t[15]\n761\tS. Kumar, Š. Sedláček, V. Lokegaonkar, F. López, W. Yu, N. Anand, H. Ryu, L. Chen, M. Plička, M. Hlaváček\n762\tet al.\n763\t, “Mmau-pro: A challenging and comprehensive benchmark for holistic evaluation of audio general intelligence,” in\n764\tProc. AAAI Conf. Artif. Intell. (AAAI)\n765\t, vol. 40, no. 27, 2026, pp. 22 688–22 697.\n766\t[16]\n767\tF. Rudzicz, A. K. Namasivayam, and T. Wolff, “The torgo database of acoustic and articulatory speech from speakers with dysarthria,”\n768\tLang. Resources Eval.\n769\t, vol. 46, no. 4, pp. 523–541, 2012.\n770\t[17]\n771\tH. Kim, M. Hasegawa-Johnson, A. Perlman, J. R. Gunderson, T. S. Huang, K. L. Watkin, S. Frame\n772\tet al.\n773\t, “Dysarthric speech database for universal access research.” in\n774\tInterspeech\n775\t, vol. 2008, 2008, pp. 1741–1744.\n776\t[18]\n777\tR. Tan and W. Zhang, “Globeaudio: A multilingual multicultural benchmark for naturalistic evaluation of large audio-language models,”\n778\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2606.08194\n779\t, 2026.\n780\t[19]\n781\tF. D. Schmidt, I. Vulić, G. Glavaš, and D. I. Adelani, “Fleurs-slu: A massively multilingual benchmark for spoken language understanding,” in\n782\tProc. Conf. Lang. Model. (COLM)\n783\t, 2025.\n784\t[20]\n785\tI. Baucells, J. Aula-Blasco, I. de Dios-Flores, S. P. Suárez, N. Perez, A. Salles, S. S. Docio, J. Falcão, J. J. Saiz, R. Sepúlveda-Torres\n786\tet al.\n787\t, “Iberobench: A benchmark for llm evaluation in iberian languages,” in\n788\tProc. Int. Conf. Comput. Linguistics (COLING)\n789\t, 2025, pp. 10 491–10 519.\n790\t[21]\n791\tP. Moure, N. Pokel, B. Bounajma, Y. Gao, R. Boehringer, L. Cheng, and S.-C. Liu, “When audio-language models fail to leverage multimodal context for dysarthric speech recognition,”\n792\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2605.02782\n793\t, 2026.\n794\t[22]\n795\tH. Zhu, L. Ye, W. Kang, Z. Yao, L. Guo, F. Kuang, Z. Han, W. Zhuang, L. Lin, and D. Povey, “Omnivoice: Towards omnilingual zero-shot text-to-speech with diffusion language models,”\n796\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2604.00688\n797\t, 2026.\n798\t[23]\n799\tA. H. Liu, A. Ehrenberg, A. Lo, C. Denoix, C. Barreau, G. Lample, J.-M. Delignon, K. R. Chandu, P. von Platen, P. R. Muddireddy\n800\tet al.\n801\t, “Voxtral,”\n802\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2507.13264\n803\t, 2025.\n804\t[24]\n805\tA. Radford, J. W. Kim, T. Xu, G. Brockman, C. McLeavey, and I. Sutskever, “Robust speech recognition via large-scale weak supervision,” in\n806\tProc. ICML\n807\t. PMLR, 2023, pp. 28 492–28 518.\n808\t[25]\n809\tA. Yang, A. Li, B. Yang, B. Zhang, B. Hui, B. Zheng, B. Yu, C. Gao, C. Huang, C. Lv\n810\tet al.\n811\t, “Qwen3 technical report,”\n812\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2505.09388\n813\t, 2025.\n814\tMajor funding support from\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "d6b7bfaf-2bbe-47ec-b39a-3001b09acd94", "uuid": "c05694e0-2cec-476b-9142-a8978a62b737", "timestamp": "2026-07-21T07:46:16.305Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/escucha_text.txt", "content": "ESCUCHA: A Spanish Speech Benchmark for Heterogeneous Acoustic Conditions\nTitle:\nContent selection saved. Describe the issue below:\nDescription:\narXiv is now an independent nonprofit!\nLearn more\n×\nLicense: CC BY 4.0\narXiv:2607.17812v1 [cs.CL] 20 Jul 2026\nESCUCHA: A Spanish Speech Benchmark for Heterogeneous Acoustic Conditions\n1\nst\nFernando López\n†\n2\nnd\nAna Ayala\n†\n3\nrd\nGuillermo Segovia\n4\nth\nFernando Ibáñez\n5\nth\nAna Martínez\n6\nth\nPablo Gómez\n7\nth\nJordi Luque\nAbstract\nAs large audio language models (LALMs) advance, robust evaluation frameworks have become essential. In this context, Spanish speech understanding under realistic acoustic conditions has received particularly little attention. We introduce ESCUCHA, the first Spanish speech understanding benchmark designed to evaluate LALMs across heterogeneous acoustic conditions and reasoning abilities. ESCUCHA comprises 1,000 human-curated questions paired with audio, totaling 162.9 hours sourced directly “from the wild” rather than drawn from existing datasets, with durations ranging from a few seconds to over 80 minutes. The benchmark emphasizes reasoning, spanning 9 perceptual and 10 reasoning categories, and it captures linguistic diversity through multiple Spanish accents and non-normative speech. ESCUCHA further includes multi-audio questions, spoken questions, and audio instructions, and it flags which questions support open-ended evaluation. Benchmarking several state-of-the-art multimodal and speech models reveals substantial performance gaps relative to trained humans.\nI\nIntroduction\nUnderstanding auditory information is essential to machine intelligence. Numerous large audio language models (LALMs) have emerged in response, including LTU\n[\n1\n]\n, SALMONN\n[\n2\n]\n, GAMA\n[\n3\n]\n, Qwen3-Omni\n[\n4\n]\n, Kimi-Audio\n[\n5\n]\n, and Audio Flamingo 3\n[\n6\n]\n.\nEvaluating these models is critical for ranking their performance and exposing their limitations, and thereby advancing the field. Early benchmarks targeted foundational tasks such as speech recognition and speech translation\n[\n7\n,\n8\n,\n9\n,\n10\n]\n. More recent efforts evaluate perception and reasoning jointly, including MMAU\n[\n11\n]\n, MMAR\n[\n12\n]\n, SAKURA\n[\n13\n]\n, MMSU\n[\n14\n]\n, and MMAU-Pro\n[\n15\n]\n.\nDespite this growth, it remains unclear whether strong performance on existing benchmarks transfers once models move beyond English and beyond normative speech. High scores under normative, English-centric conditions do not guarantee that a model will generalize to other languages and speaker characteristics, and current benchmarks offer little guidance on the expected degradation. This concern is acute for non-normative speech: neuromotor disorders such as amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) and post-stroke conditions frequently cause dysarthria, which impairs neuromuscular control of speech, reduces articulation clarity, alters prosody, and yields variable intelligibility, all of which challenge speech recognition systems\n[\n16\n,\n17\n]\n.\nThe gap is particularly concerning for practitioners who aim to deploy LALMs in non-English contexts. Multilingual benchmarks offer only limited relief: GlobeAudio spans six languages but excludes Spanish\n[\n18\n]\n, while Fleurs-SLU\n[\n19\n]\nevaluates speech-LLMs on Spanish only as one language among many, and through a narrow set of reading-comprehension questions derived from text, whose answers are recoverable from a transcript. For Spanish specifically, initial efforts such as IberoBench\n[\n20\n]\ntarget the Iberian languages, but IberoBench is a multi-task text benchmark for the natural language understanding of large language models (LLMs) rather than a speech benchmark. For non-normative speech, meanwhile, prior work centers on transcription, leaving speech understanding uncovered\n[\n21\n]\n. More broadly, existing benchmarks concentrate on English and normative speech, rely on read or curated audio rather than audio in the wild, restrict themselves to a limited range of question types, and, being derived from existing datasets, risk train-test contamination.\nTo close this gap, we introduce\nESCUCHA\n, the first speech understanding benchmark for evaluating LALMs in Spanish, spanning both normative and non-normative speech sourced under real-world conditions.\nESCUCHA\nfollows the multiple-choice question answering (MCQA) protocol and additionally includes multi-audio comparative questions, audio instruction following (AIF), and spoken questions, which together characterize how LALMs perform on Spanish across diverse conditions. Our main contributions are as follows:\n•\nThe first\nin-the-wild\nSpanish benchmark (audio and questions) for evaluating large audio language models.\n1\n1\n1\nDownload code and annotations:\nhttps://github.com/ferugit/ESCUCHA\n•\nThe first LALM benchmark to evaluate speech understanding and reasoning over non-normative pathological speech, spanning amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) and stroke.\n•\nA broad evaluation of current LALM behavior on Spanish, covering open-weight and closed models, text-only baselines, and human performance.\nII\nThe ESCUCHA Benchmark\nII-A\nOverview\nESCUCHA\ncomprises 1,000 expert-curated questions grounded in 162.9 hours of in-the-wild Spanish audio sourced from publicly available recordings. Following the MMAU-Pro design philosophy\n[\n15\n]\n, we annotate every question along two complementary axes: the\nperceptual\nskills required to extract information from the signal, and the\nreasoning\nskills required to transform that information into an answer, yielding a multi-label taxonomy of 9 perception and 10 reasoning categories. Questions carry 1.44 perception labels and 1.14 reasoning labels on average, reflecting the compositional nature of realistic audio understanding: a single item frequently demands, for example, both paralinguistic emotion recognition and causal reasoning about speaker intent. An example appears in Figure\n1\n: the item combines non-normative speech from an ALS patient with temporal and quantitative reasoning, requiring the model to recognize two numerical values, place them on a shared timeline, and compare them.\nExample Question\nAudio context:\nA 96-second testimony in which Irene, a 28-year-old woman with non-normative speech who was diagnosed with ALS (\nELA\n), recounts the date of her diagnosis and cites the life expectancy typically given to patients with the disease.\nQuestion:\n¿Desde que le diagnosticaron la ELA, ha vivido Irene más tiempo del que se\nmenciona en el vídeo como esperanza de vida para las personas con esta\nenfermedad?\nSince Irene was diagnosed with ALS, has she lived\nlonger than the life expectancy mentioned in the video for people with this disease?\n(A)\nHa vivido menos.\nShe has lived less.\n(B)\nHa vivido más.\n✓\n\\checkmark\nShe has lived longer.\n(C)\nNo puede saberse.\nIt cannot be determined.\n(D)\nHa vivido lo mismo.\nShe has lived the same amount of time.\nPerception:\nLexical & Phrase-Level Recognition\nReasoning:\nQuantitative Reasoning (Counting/Arithmetic Comparison)\n⋅\n\\cdot\nTemporal & Ordering Reasoning\nFigure 1:\nExample of chained cross-category reasoning.\nThe question requires three steps: recognizing two numerical values (time since Irene’s diagnosis and the life expectancy she cites), mapping them onto a shared timeline, and comparing them. The most frequent failure is selecting (C)\n“No puede saberse,”\nwhich conflates the absence of an explicit comparison in the audio with genuine unknowability.\nESCUCHA also features a\ncomparative\nsubset: 254 questions (25.4%) reference two separate recordings and require the model to relate them, comparing speakers, dialects, acoustic conditions, or content across clips. Such cross-clip comparison is common in professional listening tasks. Table\nI\nsummarizes the main statistics of the benchmark.\nTABLE I:\nESCUCHA at a glance. AIF: audio instruction following;\nMCQA: multiple-choice question answering. Comparative, spoken, and non-normative are non-exclusive tags and do not partition the total.\nStatistic\nValue\nTotal questions\n1,000\nMCQA\n900\nAIF\n100\nNon-exclusive questions\nComparative (two-audio)\n254\nSpoken questions\n100\nNon-normative speech\n158\nPerception / reasoning categories\n9 / 10\nMean labels per question (perc. / reas.)\n1.44 / 1.14\nDuration per question (median / mean)\n1.4 min / 9.8 min\nDuration range\n0.1 min – 85.2 min\nTotal audio (sum over questions)\n162.9 h\nII-B\nBenchmark Creation Process\nWe construct ESCUCHA through the four-stage pipeline illustrated in Figure\n2\n.\nFigure 2:\nPipeline for constructing the ESCUCHA benchmark. The process comprises four stages: (i) target setting and refinement of the perception and reasoning categories; (ii) audio selection and authoring of questions and distractors; (iii) LLM-assisted review; and (iv) model and human evaluation.\n•\nTargets and category refinement.\nWe define the target of each question type, the categories, and the type of audio to collect, then revise the perception and reasoning taxonomy. Section\nII-C\nprovides further detail.\n•\nAudio selection and question authoring.\nWe source audio from in-the-wild YouTube recordings, favoring spontaneous speech. Annotators identify candidate videos, filter the content, author the corresponding questions and distractors, ground each item in the audio, and assign its perception and reasoning labels. For non-normative speech, we retrieve videos using Spanish queries targeting dysarthric speech, such as condition-specific keywords, interviews, and documentaries, with a preference for interviews; we then filter candidates on the basis of self-reported diagnoses, video metadata, and perceptual evidence of non-normative speech. The resulting corpus spans acoustically diverse conditions, including background noise, music, and heterogeneous recording setups.\n•\nLLM-assisted review.\nWe review each question along four dimensions with an LLM (\nGemma-4-31B-IT\n), which returns the identifiers of the items it flags for manual verification by annotators. The review checks whether the categories are correctly assigned, whether the audio is required to answer the question, whether the distractors are sufficiently challenging, and whether the question or distractors contain grammatical errors.\n•\nModel and human evaluation.\nWe benchmark a range of LALMs, text-only LLMs, and cascade systems, and we collect human judgments to establish reference performance.\nAcross all four stages, the annotation team consists of three linguists and three technical experts, all native Spanish speakers. Each item carries metadata, including source URLs, measured durations, multi-label categories, distractors, and, where applicable, pathological speaker attributes and AIF verifier identifiers.\nII-C\nTaxonomy\nWe derive our taxonomy from MMAU-Pro\n[\n15\n]\n, retaining its perception and reasoning axes while slightly redefining them. Table\nII\npresents the category counts for our benchmark.\nTABLE II:\nQuestion counts per perception and reasoning category. Counts sum to more than 1,000 because the taxonomy is multi-label.\nCategory\n#Q\nPerception\nLexical and Phrase-Level Recognition\n506\nSpeaker Identification\n324\nParalinguistic/Emotion Recognition\n181\nSpeech Activity, Turn-Taking and Overlap Detection\n115\nLanguage Identification\n87\nAudio Quality, Artifacts & Channel Characteristics\n84\nProsody Detection\n74\nSpeaker Demographics\n50\nSyntactic and Sentence-Structure Processing\n18\nReasoning\nSpeaker Intent, Pragmatics and Causal Reasoning\n221\nSemantic Abstraction and Summarization\n177\nLogical/Consistency Reasoning\n159\nGround Truth and World Knowledge Integration\n133\nQuantitative Reasoning\n121\nTemporal and Ordering Reasoning\n105\nSocial Role and Relationship Inference\n94\nComparative and Preference-Based Judgments\n62\nCross-frontier Entity Linking\n38\nCoherence and Discourse Structure\n29\nRather than enforce a uniform distribution, we prioritized questions that were challenging and well grounded in each recording over questions that would merely fill under-represented cells. This preserves difficulty while still covering every category. The co-occurrence matrix (Fig.\n3\n) characterizes the distribution that emerged. It is densely populated rather than block-diagonal: lexical recognition co-occurs with all ten reasoning categories, peaking with semantic abstraction and summarization (158), while other perceptual skills pair more selectively, such as language identification with ground-truth and world-knowledge integration (53). This mix of one broad row and several localized pairings shows that many questions combine perception and reasoning rather than isolating a single skill. A few specific pairings remain unpopulated, which we leave to future work.\nFigure 3:\nPerception\n×\n\\times\nreasoning co-occurrence across the 900 MCQA questions. AIF questions only with perception labels, were excluded. Each cell counts question label pairs; questions carrying multiple perception or reasoning labels contribute to several cells, so cell totals exceed the question count and row and column sums are not disjoint.\nII-D\nOther Tasks\nBeyond regular covered tasks,\nESCUCHA\nincludes two further subsets.\nNon-normative speech.\nA subset of 158 questions (15.8%) targets pathological speech, with per-speaker metadata covering diagnosis, sex, and intelligibility. It includes speakers with ALS (114 questions) and post-stroke speech (44), annotated by sex (123 male, 35 female). We also provide intelligibility levels for 145 of the 158 items, ranging from Low (53) and Medium/Low (71) to Medium (9) and High/Medium (12); the remaining 13 ALS items lack an intelligibility annotation.\nSpoken questions.\nWe sample 100 questions from the existing\nESCUCHA\npool, using inverse-frequency weighting over perception and reasoning categories to prioritise underrepresented classes. Only single-audio items were eligible, since the spoken question is stored as a second associated audio. The original question text is fed to the OmniVoice\n[\n22\n]\ntext-to-speech (TTS) system, which yields varied speakers and Spanish accents. At evaluation time, the written prompt is fixed (\n“Contesta a la pregunta en el audio”\n, i.e., “Answer the question in the audio”), so the model must recover the actual question entirely from the spoken audio. The choices are maintained in text.\nII-E\nAudio Duration\nThe benchmark spans four orders of magnitude in duration, from 6.7 s to 85 min per question (median 86.2 s, mean 586.5 s; for comparative items the duration is summed over both clips). Each question is assigned to one of five length buckets, reported in Table\nIII\n. The Long and Extended buckets jointly account for a quarter of the benchmark, allowing\nESCUCHA\nto stress long-context audio understanding. Figure\n4\nshows the full duration distribution.\nTABLE III:\nDistribution of questions across the five duration buckets.\nBucket\nRange\n#Q\n%\nBrief\n≤\n30\n{\\leq}30\ns\n123\n12.3\nShort\n30 s–2 min\n440\n44.0\nMedium\n2–10 min\n187\n18.7\nLong\n10–30 min\n127\n12.7\nExtended\n>\n30\n{>}30\nmin\n123\n12.3\nTotal\n1,000\n100.0\nFigure 4:\nDistribution of audio duration per question (log scale). The dashed line marks the median (86.2 s).\nII-F\nEvaluation Formats\nESCUCHA contains two evaluation formats. Most of the benchmark (900 questions, 90%) follows an MCQA protocol with 2–4 options (848 four-choice, 45 three-choice, 7 two-choice), enabling deterministic scoring. Independently of format, each question is annotated for whether the options are required: 712 (71.2%) are answerable without them, allowing open-ended evaluation, and 288 (28.8%) require them.\nThe remaining 100 questions (10%) are\naudio instruction-following\n(AIF) items: open-ended tasks in which the instruction is delivered in the audio rather than the text prompt, and the response must satisfy that spoken constraint, checked by a deterministic verifier. To produce the spoken instructions, we also use the OmniVoice\n[\n22\n]\n. This design jointly probes audio comprehension and instruction following: the model must first recover the instruction from the signal and then obey it. We cover six constraint types:\n•\nKeyword usage\n(24): include a specified connector or phrase, e.g.,\nsin embargo\n(“however”), or at least one numeral.\n•\nLength\n(22): meet an exact, minimum, maximum, or bounded word or sentence count, e.g., exactly three sentences.\n•\nWord exclusion\n(18): avoid a specified word, expression, or punctuation mark, e.g.,\nmuy\n(“very”).\n•\nOpenings/closings\n(16): begin with a fixed prefix or end with a fixed suffix, e.g.,\nEn resumen\n(“In summary”).\n•\nFormatting\n(12): adopt a structural form, e.g., a numbered list or sections delimited by\n##\nheaders.\n•\nStyle\n(8): e.g., write in lowercase only, pose the answer as questions, or repeat a keyword a number of times.\nA constraint can occasionally be met without genuine compliance; word exclusion, for instance, may be satisfied by chance. The expected random-guessing accuracy is 25.61% on the MCQA subset and 23.05% on the full benchmark.\nIII\nExperimental Setup\nWe evaluate\nESCUCHA\nacross four system families: end-to-end LALMs, a cascaded ASR-plus-LLM pipeline, text-only LLMs, and human and random baselines. Thus, we separate genuine audio understanding from what is recoverable through transcription alone and language bias. In our setup, multi-audio items are presented as their component clips concatenated with one second of silence between them, and all experiments run on an NVIDIA DGX Spark GPU.\nIII-A\nLALMs\nWe evaluate several LALMs, covering open and proprietary systems of varying scale:\nAudio-Flamingo-3\n(8.3B)\n[\n6\n]\n,\nQwen2.5-Omni\n(7B),\nQwen3-Omni-30B-A3B\n[\n4\n]\n,\nVoxtral-Mini\n(3B)\n[\n23\n]\n,\nGemma-4-12B-IT\n, and\nGemini-2.5-Flash\n.\nIII-B\nCascaded Systems\nTo test whether audio understanding is required at all, or whether transcription suffices, we evaluate a cascade. This is a natural baseline given that lexical recognition is the most represented perception category. We transcribe each audio with\nWhisper-Large-v3\n[\n24\n]\nand answer with\nQwen3-4B-Instruct-2507\n[\n25\n]\n.\nIII-C\nText-Only LLMs\nExtending the cascade logic, we evaluate text-only LLMs that never see the raw audio. These receive the questions and choices with no audio. We include\nGemma-4-31B-IT\n,\nGemma-4-12B-IT\n, and\nQwen3-4B-Instruct-2507\n[\n25\n]\n.\nIII-D\nEvaluation Protocol\nMCQA.\nEach item presents a question with\nN\nN\nlabeled options; the model must respond as\n<letter>.<justification>\n. Scoring is exact-match: correct if the output matches the gold string case-insensitively or its first parsed letter indexes the gold option.\nAIF.\nAudio instruction-following items are open-ended: a deterministic\nverifier\nfunction with a parameter dictionary is applied to the output, returning true or false. No model-based judge is used, so scoring is fully reproducible.\nIV\nResults\nTable\nIV\nreports accuracy across all models and subsets. The trained human annotator reaches 90.10% overall, far above the best model (74.40%), establishing a wide human–model gap on\nESCUCHA\n.\nTABLE IV:\nESCUCHA benchmark results (accuracy %). Best result per column is\nbolded\n. Pathological and Normative are MCQA subsets; Spoken Q contains items whose question is embedded in the audio.\nModel\nSize\nMCQA\nAIF\nPathological\nNormative\nSpoken Q\nOverall\nBaselines\nRandom\n–\n25.61\n0.00\n25.32\n25.67\n25.75\n23.05\nAlways 1st\n–\n26.22\n0.00\n24.05\n26.68\n23.00\n23.60\nAlways 2nd\n–\n24.33\n0.00\n27.22\n23.72\n23.00\n21.90\nAlways 3rd\n–\n26.22\n0.00\n25.95\n26.28\n30.00\n23.60\nAlways 4th\n–\n23.22\n0.00\n22.78\n23.32\n24.00\n20.90\nHuman\n–\n91.33\n79.00\n93.04\n90.97\n93.00\n90.10\nAudio Models\nAudio-Flamingo-3-HF\n8.3B\n51.56\n32.00\n55.06\n50.81\n64.00\n49.60\nGemini-2.5-Flash\n–\n52.67\n54.00\n36.71\n56.06\n53.00\n52.80\nGemma-4-12B-IT\n12B\n48.11\n60.00\n36.08\n50.67\n49.00\n49.30\nQwen2.5-Omni-7B\n7B\n50.22\n54.00\n44.94\n51.35\n58.00\n50.60\nQwen3-Omni-30B-A3B\n30B (A3B)\n72.89\n88.00\n74.68\n72.51\n77.00\n74.40\nVoxtral-Mini-3B-2507\n3B\n50.22\n40.00\n51.90\n49.87\n55.00\n49.20\nCascaded\nwhisper-large-v3 + Qwen3-4B-Instruct-2507\n4B\n59.00\n69.00\n63.92\n57.95\n59.00\n60.00\nText-Only Models\nGemma-4-31B-IT\n31B\n23.00\n31.00\n23.42\n22.91\n33.00\n23.80\nGemma-4-12B-IT (text)\n12B\n18.11\n32.00\n18.35\n18.06\n23.00\n19.50\nQwen3-4B-Instruct-2507\n4B\n42.11\n31.00\n46.20\n41.24\n48.00\n41.00\nAmong audio models,\nQwen3-Omni-30B-A3B\nstands out at 74.40% overall and leads every column among models, including a striking 88.00% on AIF that exceeds even the human score of 79.00% on that subset. Every other audio model falls between 49 and 53% overall, confirming that\nESCUCHA\nposes a genuine challenge.\nA consistent pattern is the drop from normative to pathological speech.\nGemini-2.5-Flash\nand\nGemma-4-12B-IT\nlose 19 and 15 percentage points, respectively, on pathological items, whereas\nAudio-Flamingo-3\n,\nQwen3-Omni-30B-A3B\n, and\nVoxtral-Mini\nhold or slightly improve. This asymmetry indicates that pathological speech remains a weak point.\nComparison with MMAU-Pro\n[\n15\n]\nadds context:\nAudio-Flamingo-3\nreaches 58.8% on the MMAU-Pro speech subset but 49.60% here, and\nQwen2.5-Omni-7B\ndrops similarly, from 57.4% to 50.60%. The two benchmarks are not directly comparable: they differ in question design, language, and the inclusion of pathological speech, but the gaps suggest\nESCUCHA\nis at least as discriminative and harder for models with limited Spanish coverage.\nThe cascaded system (\nWhisper-Large-v3\n+\nQwen3-4B-Instruct-2507\n) achieves 60.00% overall, outperforming every single audio model except\nQwen3-Omni-30B-A3B\n. Its advantage is most pronounced on AIF (69.00%) and pathological items (63.92%), supporting the view that a large fraction of\nESCUCHA\nquestions are grounded in lexical understanding.\nAll models receive the same system prompt, and none is instructed to guess under missing-modality conditions. The text-only\nQwen3-4B-Instruct-2507\nreaches 41.00% overall, well above the random baseline (23.05%) and comparable to several audio systems, which we attribute to partial solvability from question structure and language priors. We therefore suggest treating this text-only model as a lower-bound baseline, alongside the positional controls, in future evaluations. The two text-only\nGemma-4\nvariants instead score near random (23.80% and 19.50%): lacking audio, they refuse a large fraction of items, 53% for\nGemma-4-31B-IT\nand 32% for\nGemma-4-12B-IT\n, with each refusal scored as incorrect and outputs such as requests to supply the audio for analysis.\nV\nLimitations\nSeveral factors qualify our results. The human upper bound is optimistic: the evaluator is a trained linguist, so the reported 90.10% may differ from a regular person. On the AIF subset, some items can be answered correctly from the written instruction alone, without processing the audio, which partially inflates AIF scores and means the task does not exclusively measure audio instruction following. The pathological-speech subset is grounded in self-reported diagnoses targeting diverse speech understanding instead of clinical usage.\nThe evaluation is also uneven across models and axes.\nGemini-2.5-Flash\nsupports long-form audio architecturally, but a payload limit in our evaluation pipeline forced us to exclude items above a size threshold, biasing its results toward shorter items and preventing a direct comparison with models run on the full set. More broadly,\nESCUCHA\ncovers speech exclusively, so results do not generalize to music, environmental sound, or audio effects, and the benchmark is constructed entirely in Spanish, meaning scores for models with limited Spanish data conflate audio understanding with language coverage. Cross-lingual comparisons against English-centric benchmarks such as MMAU-Pro should be made with care. Finally, the taxonomy is lexically unbalanced, with lexical and phrase-level recognition dominating the perception axis, so per-category scores in sparsely populated cells rest on few items.\nVI\nConclusions\nWe introduced\nESCUCHA\n, the first in-the-wild Spanish speech benchmark for large audio-language models, and the first to evaluate reasoning over non-normative pathological speech. It pairs 1,000 curated questions with 162.9 hours of audio, annotated along a multi-label taxonomy of nine perception and ten reasoning categories, and combines MCQA with comparative multi-audio items, audio instruction following, and spoken questions.\nOur evaluation reveals a wide human–model gap: the best system reaches 74.40% overall against 90.10% for a trained annotator, with most audio models near 50%. Two findings stand out. Several models degrade markedly on pathological speech, a persistent weak point for LALMs trained on clean, read audio. And a cascaded ASR-plus-LLM pipeline outperforms every single audio model but one, indicating that much of the benchmark is grounded in lexical understanding recoverable from a transcript, while the residual gap to\nQwen3-Omni-30B-A3B\nmarks where genuine acoustic reasoning still matters.\nFuture work includes broadening the pathological subset with further neurological conditions, and populating the currently sparse perception-reasoning pairings.\nAI-Generated Content Disclosure\nWe used a generative AI to assist in paraphrasing and improving clarity and grammar in parts of the manuscript; all generated content was reviewed and validated by the authors.\nReferences\n[1]\nY. Gong, H. Luo, A. H. Liu, L. Karlinsky, and J. Glass, “Listen, think, and understand,” in\nProc. ICLR\n, 2024.\n[2]\nG. Sun, W. Yu, C. Tang, X. Chen, T. Tan, W. Li, L. Lu, Z. Ma, Y. Wang, and C. Zhang, “video-salmonn: Speech-enhanced audio-visual large language models,” in\nProc. ICML\n, 2024.\n[3]\nS. Ghosh, S. Kumar, A. Seth, C. K. R. Evuru, U. Tyagi, S. Sakshi, O. Nieto, R. Duraiswami, and D. Manocha, “GAMA: A large audio-language model with advanced audio understanding and complex reasoning abilities,” in\nProc. EMNLP\n. Miami, Florida, USA: ACL, 2024, pp. 6288–6313. [Online]. Available:\nhttps://aclanthology.org/2024.emnlp-main.361/\n[4]\nJ. Xu, Z. Guo, H. Hu, Y. Chu, X. Wang, J. He, Y. Wang, X. Shi, T. He, X. Zhu, Y. Lv, Y. Wang, D. Guo, H. Wang, L. Ma, P. Zhang, X. Zhang, H. Hao, Z. Guo, B. Yang, B. Zhang, Z. Ma, X. Wei, S. Bai, K. Chen, X. Liu, P. Wang, M. Yang, D. Liu, X. Ren, B. Zheng, R. Men, F. Zhou, B. Yu, J. Yang, L. Yu, J. Zhou, and J. Lin, “Qwen3-omni technical report,” 2025. [Online]. Available:\nhttps://arxiv.org/abs/2509.17765\n[5]\nD. Ding, Z. Ju, Y. Leng, S. Liu, T. Liu, Z. Shang, K. Shen, W. Song, X. Tan, H. Tang\net al.\n, “Kimi-audio technical report,”\narXiv preprint arXiv:2504.18425\n, 2025.\n[6]\nS. Ghosh, A. Goel, J. Kim, S. Kumar, Z. Kong, S. gil Lee, C.-H. H. Yang, R. Duraiswami, D. Manocha, R. Valle, and B. Catanzaro, “Audio flamingo 3: Advancing audio intelligence with fully open large audio language models,” in\nProc. Adv. Neural Inf. Process. Syst. (NeurIPS)\n, 2025. [Online]. Available:\nhttps://openreview.net/forum?id=FjByDpDVIO\n[7]\nC.-y. Huang, K.-H. Lu, S.-H. Wang, C.-Y. Hsiao, C.-Y. Kuan, H. Wu, S. Arora, K.-W. Chang, J. Shi, Y. Peng\net al.\n, “Dynamic-superb: Towards a dynamic, collaborative, and comprehensive instruction-tuning benchmark for speech,” in\nProc. ICASSP\n. IEEE, 2024, pp. 12 136–12 140.\n[8]\nQ. Yang, J. Xu, W. Liu, Y. Chu, Z. Jiang, X. Zhou, Y. Leng, Y. Lv, Z. Zhao, C. Zhou\net al.\n, “Air-bench: Benchmarking large audio-language models via generative comprehension,” in\nProc. ACL\n. Bangkok, Thailand: ACL, Aug. 2024, pp. 1979–1998. [Online]. Available:\nhttps://aclanthology.org/2024.acl-long.109/\n[9]\nB. Wang, X. Zou, G. Lin, S. Sun, Z. Liu, W. Zhang, Z. Liu, A. Aw, and N. F. Chen, “Audiobench: A universal benchmark for audio large language models,” in\nProc. NAACL:HLT\n, Albuquerque, New Mexico, 2025, pp. 4297–4316.\n[10]\nC.-y. Huang, W.-C. Chen, S.-w. Yang, A. T. Liu, C.-A. Li, Y.-X. Lin, W.-C. Tseng, A. Diwan, Y.-J. Shih, J. Shi\net al.\n, “Dynamic-superb phase-2: A collaboratively expanding benchmark for measuring the capabilities of spoken language models with 180 tasks,” in\nProc. ICLR\n, 2025.\n[11]\nS. Sakshi, U. Tyagi, S. Kumar, A. Seth, R. Selvakumar, O. Nieto, R. Duraiswami, S. Ghosh, and D. Manocha, “MMAU: A massive multi-task audio understanding and reasoning benchmark,” in\nProc. ICLR\n, 2024.\n[12]\nZ. Ma, Y. Ma, Y. Zhu, C. Yang, Y.-W. Chao, R. Xu, W. Chen, Y. Chen, Z. Chen, J. Cong\net al.\n, “Mmar: A challenging benchmark for deep reasoning in speech, audio, music, and their mix,” in\nProc. Adv. Neural Inf. Process. Syst. (NeurIPS) Datasets and Benchmarks Track\n, 2025.\n[13]\nC.-K. Yang, N. Ho, Y.-T. Piao, and H. yi Lee, “SAKURA: On the Multi-hop Reasoning of Large Audio-Language Models Based on Speech and Audio Information,” in\nInterspeech\n, 2025, pp. 1788–1792.\n[14]\nD. Wang, J. Wu, J. Li, D. Yang, X. Chen, T. Zhang, and H. Meng, “MMSU: A Massive Multi-task Spoken Language Understanding and Reasoning Benchmark,”\narXiv preprint arXiv:2506.04779\n, 2025.\n[15]\nS. Kumar, Š. Sedláček, V. Lokegaonkar, F. López, W. Yu, N. Anand, H. Ryu, L. Chen, M. Plička, M. Hlaváček\net al.\n, “Mmau-pro: A challenging and comprehensive benchmark for holistic evaluation of audio general intelligence,” in\nProc. AAAI Conf. Artif. Intell. (AAAI)\n, vol. 40, no. 27, 2026, pp. 22 688–22 697.\n[16]\nF. Rudzicz, A. K. Namasivayam, and T. Wolff, “The torgo database of acoustic and articulatory speech from speakers with dysarthria,”\nLang. Resources Eval.\n, vol. 46, no. 4, pp. 523–541, 2012.\n[17]\nH. Kim, M. Hasegawa-Johnson, A. Perlman, J. R. Gunderson, T. S. Huang, K. L. Watkin, S. Frame\net al.\n, “Dysarthric speech database for universal access research.” in\nInterspeech\n, vol. 2008, 2008, pp. 1741–1744.\n[18]\nR. Tan and W. Zhang, “Globeaudio: A multilingual multicultural benchmark for naturalistic evaluation of large audio-language models,”\narXiv preprint arXiv:2606.08194\n, 2026.\n[19]\nF. D. Schmidt, I. Vulić, G. Glavaš, and D. I. Adelani, “Fleurs-slu: A massively multilingual benchmark for spoken language understanding,” in\nProc. Conf. Lang. Model. (COLM)\n, 2025.\n[20]\nI. Baucells, J. Aula-Blasco, I. de Dios-Flores, S. P. Suárez, N. Perez, A. Salles, S. S. Docio, J. Falcão, J. J. Saiz, R. Sepúlveda-Torres\net al.\n, “Iberobench: A benchmark for llm evaluation in iberian languages,” in\nProc. Int. Conf. Comput. Linguistics (COLING)\n, 2025, pp. 10 491–10 519.\n[21]\nP. Moure, N. Pokel, B. Bounajma, Y. Gao, R. Boehringer, L. Cheng, and S.-C. Liu, “When audio-language models fail to leverage multimodal context for dysarthric speech recognition,”\narXiv preprint arXiv:2605.02782\n, 2026.\n[22]\nH. Zhu, L. Ye, W. Kang, Z. Yao, L. Guo, F. Kuang, Z. Han, W. Zhuang, L. Lin, and D. Povey, “Omnivoice: Towards omnilingual zero-shot text-to-speech with diffusion language models,”\narXiv preprint arXiv:2604.00688\n, 2026.\n[23]\nA. H. Liu, A. Ehrenberg, A. Lo, C. Denoix, C. Barreau, G. Lample, J.-M. Delignon, K. R. Chandu, P. von Platen, P. R. Muddireddy\net al.\n, “Voxtral,”\narXiv preprint arXiv:2507.13264\n, 2025.\n[24]\nA. Radford, J. W. Kim, T. Xu, G. Brockman, C. McLeavey, and I. Sutskever, “Robust speech recognition via large-scale weak supervision,” in\nProc. ICML\n. PMLR, 2023, pp. 28 492–28 518.\n[25]\nA. Yang, A. Li, B. Yang, B. Zhang, B. Hui, B. Zheng, B. Yu, C. Gao, C. Huang, C. Lv\net al.\n, “Qwen3 technical report,”\narXiv preprint arXiv:2505.09388\n, 2025.\nMajor funding support from", "numLines": 814, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 814}}}
