{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-80837439e59c5a82", "type": "tool_result", "content": "=== at 95 ===\nMultilingual Multicultural Benchmark for Naturalistic Evaluation of Large Audio-Language Models // Restore the saved color scheme preference, or // enact the browser preference if \"automatic\", // without expecting DOM load to have completed. // // Also restore any saved readingmo\n\n=== at 2365 ===\n PDF Abstract 1 Introduction 2 GlobeAudio Dataset 2.1 Design Considerations 2.2 Language Selection and Considerations 2.3 Data Collection and Processing 2.4 Data Annotation 2.5 Dataset Breakdown 3 Experimental Setup 3.1 Model Selection Closed-source LALMs Open-source LALMs Cascad\n\n=== at 2972 ===\nUniversal Evaluation Efforts Multilingual Evaluation 6 Conclusion 7 Limitations Language Coverage Data distribution References A Appendix A.1 Prompts used in Inference Overview Prompts for Open and Closed-Source Models Prompts for Cascade Pipelines A.2 GlobeAudio ’s Question Exam\n\n=== at 3185 ===\nodels Prompts for Cascade Pipelines A.2 GlobeAudio ’s Question Examples of each language A.3 yt-dlp Commands and Parameters License: arXiv.org perpetual non-exclusive license arXiv:2606.08194v1 [cs.CL] 06 Jun 2026 GlobeAudio: A Multilingual Multicultural Benchmark for Naturalisti\n\n=== at 3413 ===\nMultilingual Multicultural Benchmark for Naturalistic Evaluation of Large Audio-Language Models Ryner Tan, Wenxuan Zhang Singapore University of Technology and Design ryner_tan@mymail.sutd.edu.sg , wxzhang@sutd.edu.sg Abstract Large Audio-Language Models (LALMs) integrate audio p\n\n=== at 3572 ===\n Design ryner_tan@mymail.sutd.edu.sg , wxzhang@sutd.edu.sg Abstract Large Audio-Language Models (LALMs) integrate audio perception and language understanding within a unified framework, enabling a wide range of real-world applications. Despite recent advances, evaluation for LALM\n\n=== at 3627 ===\n.sg Abstract Large Audio-Language Models (LALMs) integrate audio perception and language understanding within a unified framework, enabling a wide range of real-world applications. Despite recent advances, evaluation for LALMs remains heavily underspecified relative to real-world\n\n=== at 4172 ===\nio consists of 5,637 multiple-choice questions across six typologically diverse languages, expertly crafted by native speakers grounded on naturally occurring audio. In order to do well, models must possess higher-level auditory reasoning skills and culturally grounded interpreta\n\n=== at 4636 ===\ntural acoustic conditions, particularly for open-source models and low-resource languages. These findings highlight critical limitations of current LALMs and underscore the importance of naturalistic audio evaluation for future audio-language systems. GlobeAudio can be found at h\n\n=== at 4790 ===\nand underscore the importance of naturalistic audio evaluation for future audio-language systems. GlobeAudio can be found at https://huggingface.co/datasets/iNLP-Lab/GlobeAudio . GlobeAudio: A Multilingual Multicultural Benchmark for Naturalistic Evaluation of Large Audio-Languag\n\n=== at 4983 ===\nMultilingual Multicultural Benchmark for Naturalistic Evaluation of Large Audio-Language Models Ryner Tan, Wenxuan Zhang Singapore University of Technology and Design ryner_tan@mymail.sutd.edu.sg , wxzhang@sutd.edu.sg 1 Introduction Large Audio-Language Models (LALMs) are an emer\n\n=== at 5148 ===\nn ryner_tan@mymail.sutd.edu.sg , wxzhang@sutd.edu.sg 1 Introduction Large Audio-Language Models (LALMs) are an emerging class of systems designed to comprehend, process, and generate responses directly from audio inputs Lakhotia et al. ( 2021 ); Chu et al. ( 2024 ); Fang et al. (\n\n=== at 5693 ===\ng et al. ( 2025 ); Shakhadri et al. ( 2025 ) , LALMs unify audio processing and language understanding, enabling tasks like spoken QA and speech translation for diverse applications such as virtual assistants and educational tools Su et al. ( 2025 ); Deshmukh et al. ( 2023 ) . Dr\n\n=== at 7241 ===\nchmidt et al. ( 2025 ); Beyene et al. ( 2025 ) are scalable and largely broaden language coverage, their reliance on automated translation compromises multicultural validity by flattening culturally grounded references. In addition, current evaluations fail to capture acoustic re\n\n=== at 8976 ===\nnally high inter-annotator consensus at 95.5% . In total, GlobeAudio covers six languages spanning high to low-resource settings and diverse language families, offering a total of 5,637 expertly crafted multiple-choice questions in total as shown in Figure 1 . Consequently, we co\n\n=== at 9037 ===\nbeAudio covers six languages spanning high to low-resource settings and diverse language families, offering a total of 5,637 expertly crafted multiple-choice questions in total as shown in Figure 1 . Consequently, we conduct a comprehensive evaluation of representative LALMs as w\n\n=== at 9665 ===\ntrail considerably behind their closed-source counterparts, and in low-resource languages such as Thai and Bengali. Through targeted ablations and extensive analysis, we further demonstrate the high fidelity of GlobeAudio and reveal a surprising alignment behaviour: LALMs perform\n\n=== at 9933 ===\nALMs perform better when evaluated with questions and transcripts in the source language, instead of in English which is a comparatively higher resource language. In summary, our contributions are threefold: • We introduce GlobeAudio , a multilingual, multicultural benchmark for \n\n=== at 10006 ===\nsource language, instead of in English which is a comparatively higher resource language. In summary, our contributions are threefold: • We introduce GlobeAudio , a multilingual, multicultural benchmark for naturalistic audio understanding, comprising 5,637 human-authored and rig\n\n=== at 10237 ===\nstanding, comprising 5,637 human-authored and rigorously verified MCQs across 6 languages and diverse real-world contexts. • We extensively benchmark various state-of-the-art LALMs, spanning closed-source, open-source models across various model families, and reveal substantial p\n\n=== at 10507 ===\nstantial performance gaps, particularly for open-source models and low-resource languages. • Through targeted ablations and cross-lingual studies, we uncover a counter-intuitive but consistent advantage of source-language evaluation over English translation, and the linguistic–cu\n\n=== at 10640 ===\ngual studies, we uncover a counter-intuitive but consistent advantage of source-language evaluation over English translation, and the linguistic–cultural grounding in shaping LALM performance. Figure 2: GlobeAudio ’s data preparation pipeline, from curation to rigorous annotation\n\n=== at 11527 ===\nlobeAudio is constructed by native speakers with lived experience in the target languages and cultures. • In-the-Wild Audio Sources : Spoken language in real-world environments is often characterized by background noise, prosody, overlapping speakers, informal delivery, and uncon\n\n=== at 11588 ===\nence in the target languages and cultures. • In-the-Wild Audio Sources : Spoken language in real-world environments is often characterized by background noise, prosody, overlapping speakers, informal delivery, and unconstrained recording conditions Nagrani et al. ( 2020 ) . To ca\n\n=== at 12602 ===\nobing holistic auditory comprehension. Linguistic Properties Dataset Statistics Language (Code) CC Size Isochrony Genus Script Clip length QA length (Q/A) Total English (en) 42.60 High, Str Germanic Latin 25.72 53.8 / 22.9 1,274 Russian (ru) 6.15 High, Str Slavic Cyrillic 25.69 3\n\n=== at 13268 ===\nllable-timed) Table 2: Dataset Composition of GlobeAudio , sorted by decreasing language resource level. We report weighted averages for clip length (in seconds) and QA length (in characters), with per-language count. 2.2 Language Selection and Considerations Guided by the above \n\n=== at 13390 ===\nd averages for clip length (in seconds) and QA length (in characters), with per-language count. 2.2 Language Selection and Considerations Guided by the above design principles, we aim to construct an evaluation set that meaningfully probes both linguistic and cultural variability\n\n=== at 13410 ===\nlength (in seconds) and QA length (in characters), with per-language count. 2.2 Language Selection and Considerations Guided by the above design principles, we aim to construct an evaluation set that meaningfully probes both linguistic and cultural variability in real-world speec\n\n=== at 13627 ===\nes both linguistic and cultural variability in real-world speech understanding. Language selection is therefore driven by a combination of complementary criteria, including geographical coverage, resource availability, diversity in writing systems, and diversity in phonological c\n\n=== at 13888 ===\ny in phonological characteristics. Based on these considerations, we select six languages: English (United States), Chinese (China), Thai (Thailand), Russian (Russia), Bengali (India) and Singlish (Singapore). Collectively, this set spans multiple language families (Indo-European\n\n=== at 14056 ===\nBengali (India) and Singlish (Singapore). Collectively, this set spans multiple language families (Indo-European, Sino-Tibetan, Tai–Kadai, and creole varieties), covers a wide range of geographic regions, and reflects substantial variation in resource availability. As shown in Ta\n\n=== at 14370 ===\n Size (CC Size) as a proxy for the resource level, it covers from high-resource languages such as English, to comparatively much lower-resource settings such as Thai and Bengali. The selected languages also differ markedly in script systems and spoken characteristics: the inclusi\n\n=== at 14482 ===\nmparatively much lower-resource settings such as Thai and Bengali. The selected languages also differ markedly in script systems and spoken characteristics: the inclusion of Singlish enables the